nd girl in Somali are the same but the stress and the tone in the two words is what differentiates them. %0a%3c %0a%3c It would be interesting to study how difficult native English speakers find it to pronounce words in Somali (or other tonal languages). I imagine it would be much more difficult than trying to pronounce words that do not have tonal differences. This also leads me to wonder if non-tonal languages are capable of evolving to take on tonal qualities, or if language is not capable of taking on a whole new feature but only new words. %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://www.babbel.com/en/magazine/tonal-languages%0a%3c https://www.mustgo.com/worldlanguages/somali/#:~:text=The%2520tonal%2520system%2520of%2520Somali,in%2520languages%2520such%2520as%2520Chinese.%0a%3c https://phoible.org/inventories/view/127%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
